{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fc9e04d2-629e-47ae-bbec-1dc6369e537a","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface**:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n3. **Inject the interface** into classes that need file I/O.\n4. **Mock it in tests** using your preferred mocking framework.\n\nAlternatively, use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with a `MockFileSystem` for testing, saving you from writing your own wrapper.\n\n```csharp\n// With System.IO.Abstractions:\npublic class MyService\n{\n    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n    public string Load(string path) => _fs.File.ReadAllText(path);\n}\n\n// In tests:\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>\n{\n    { \"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{}\") }\n});\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\n```\n\nThis keeps your production code unchanged in behavior while making every file operation fully testable and mockable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"51dfa357-eb3b-4a94-9cc1-f44cbe222f54","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":375,"requestId":"9834:C2332:114B6B2:15B9CC6:69FFE5C6"},"id":"2c4a3d10-7406-458f-868c-a6e40177913f","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:56:30.739Z","parentId":"ac49440a-537b-4cd2-8591-95109db11572"}
